Geeetech i3prob

  • Nothing but problem after problem. Low manufacturing quality. Motherboard 2nd z-motor connection soldered upside down.

Creality cr-10 s4

  • The good - solid build - prints very well, huge build area
  • The bad - Firmware updates not easily accessible, bed heating insufficient. Needs insulation and patience or a keenovo silicone heater.

Tevo Tornado

  • The good - solid build - prints very well, bigbuild area, well designed heating bed using a solid state relay and insulated bed. Easy firmware access
  • The bad - print adhesive sheet bubbling. Will be switching to glass. Bed screws not flush to the bed.

bio:
I make all kinds of things. My work involves 3D BIM, Design prototyping, IT support and application Programming. I wear many hats.

Its been a while since I uploaded anything. My PrintRbot simple's main board died again a while ago, and considering PrintRbot recently went out of business, I decided to buy a new kit printer, The Tevo tarantula. This printer had several issues and in the long run I found I hated its design, and several other things about it. So much so I tore it down and decided to see what I could make of it with a major redesign. However this was proving difficult without a 3d printer to make parts, so I caved and decided to buy the Qidi Technology's X-pro. While the build area is not large as the Tevo's, The printer makes up for it in build quality and other features like wifi / lan cable connections, Low noise while printing etc. I'm very pleased with the Qidi, though I plan to see what I can make of the Tevo parts still.

Now that I can reliably print again, I can continue with some of my projects. Not all will be RC related, or atleast not all airplane related so keep an eye out for some fun and or useful stuff.

I am very pleased so many of you have downloaded my models. I hope printing them has worked out well. Feel free to message or comment on the results or if you have had issues.

WAS - can move down - (To be brief:
At this point in time - Oktober 2017, I know only the teknicalities of machines and their functions. I have not laid a string of filament, nor focused on a line of code.

The Prusa clone arrived - its purpose, inauguration into 3d software-hardware interface to produce required parts in conjuction with the workshop facilities and homesteading tooling. ) )

*
Meaning, thinking making, fixing, getting stuck n thinking a lot more -

These were some formulations that make me smile :-)
It means to build CNC machine/s - to teach basics, help with replacement parts, and help towards understanding and utilising the potential for self help, through this hardware/software interface.

Likely, I won’t have much time for it but the above is the direction - others would be welcome to use machine, contributing to the said expression.

Well, I don't exactly live where others, when there are any, seem to relate - whilst for me, 'making' is basically artisanship and its products in relation to relevant requirements - and equally the making of the tools with which we 'make'. Including from a lathe too,l a firestick or a latchet needle for working rope/thread. The ability to program a curve and execute with CNC, the construction of moving mechanisms with precis tolerance, and so on - Fascinating, though perhaps sometimes distracting. Thus 'repair' and tooling requirements can be vastly improved for the individual and all viable results shared.
I also weld and machine. Same reason. Perceived need and fascination.

Until future editing, that may help you who came here to gain an understanding of what movement as it were, brought me here to the realm of makers with a communal reality.

I thank all who have contributed to this and continue to do so. The designs I use, I will remember ...
What can take but a short time might never be achieved on my own so thanks is emminently due.

Pekka Salokannel is an international award-winning Industrial Designer from Finland whose passion lies in 3D printed product design. Upon graduating from Lahti Institute of Design, Pekka worked as a designer in Golla. In 2012 he joined Tinkercad, as responsible for educational content, and also worked together closely with Makerbot, Mozilla Festival and 3D Printshow. Early 2013 he founded Fabrigate, offering consultation, design and educational services with clients such as Shapeways, Cubify and Twikit. Pekka is an ambassador for 3D printing and has been a guest speaker, giving lectures and workshops in UK, China, Russia and Finland. He has his own brand Colors of Birch, a 3D printed eyewear and jewelry fashion brand which has been exhibited at Paris Fashion Week, Amsterdam and Beijing. He is currently developing Kokosom brand as one of the co-founders of this 3D printed custom eyewear company.

English:

Hello my Copter friends, I am Julian Mauntainman (JB-Copter) and started the Hobby FPV in 2016. All experiences and what I learned through the hobby I want to share with you. The goal is to make it easier and cheaper to get started with this wonderful hobby. I am studying mechanical engineering at the Technical University of Darmstadt. On my Youtube channel I give you valuable tips/tricks, show you reviews and test UAV/UAS´s, upload flight videos, give instructions for rebuilding and guide you through the hobby FPV. I wish you a lot of fun on my channel, and of course I'm looking forward to an ABO!

German:

Hallo meine Copterfreunde, ich bin Julian Mauntainman (JB-Copter) und startete das Hobby FPV im Jahr 2016. Alle Erfahrungen und was ich mit durch das Hobby gelernt habe, möchte ich mit euch teilen. Das Ziel ist es, den Einstieg in dieses wunderschöne Hobby leichter und vor allem günstiger zu ermöglichen. Ich studiere an der Technischen Universität Darmstadt Lehramt mit Maschinenbau. Auf meinem Youtube Kanal gebe ich euch wertvolle Tips/Tricks, zeige euch Reviews und teste UAV/UAS´s, lade Flugvideos hoch, gebe Anleitungen zum Nachbauen und leite euch durch das Hobby FPV. Ich Wünsche euch viel Spaß auf meinem Kanal, und freue mich natürlich über ein ABO!
